<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="114" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1436,151,863]" pageId="9" pageNumber="114">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,802,827]" pageId="9" pageNumber="114">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific name is derived from the Latin 
<emphasis box="[852,970,803,827]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="114">incurvulus</emphasis>
(recurved), referring to both sides of the socius arched towards each other in the male genitalia.
</paragraph>
